From: Markus Fritsche <mfritsche@reauktion.de>
Subject: [PATCH] v4l2_video_decoder: floor capture pool at 16 buffers
Date: 2026-04-28

Background
----------
`V4L2VideoDecoder::ContinueChangeResolution` (media/gpu/v4l2/v4l2_video_decoder.cc:1204)
sizes the V4L2 CAPTURE buffer pool as `num_codec_reference_frames + 2`
when V4L2 is the buffer allocator (V4L2_MEMORY_MMAP). For H.264 main
profile the codec reference count is 4, yielding a pool of 6 buffers.

Chrome's pipeline depth between V4L2 dequeue and `wl_buffer.release`
on a wayland compositor is also approximately 6:

   1. V4L2 dequeue side (one buffer being decoded by the driver)
   2. Media frame queue (one frame in transit to the renderer)
   3. Viz compositor (one frame being prepared for submission)
   4. wl_subsurface attached and pending parent commit
   5. wl_subsurface attached, parent committed, awaiting compositor
      paint
   6. wl_buffer waiting for the compositor's release event after
      its present cycle

Sum equals capture pool size, leaving zero headroom. Any single
compositor scheduling jitter event — a missed vsync, a brief
contention spike — exhausts the pool. The V4L2 driver has no free
buffers to fill, the V4L2DevicePoller stops polling, the decoder
backend parks waiting for a free CAPTURE buffer that will never
come back, and the pipeline deadlocks. mpv with `--vo=gpu-next`
on the same compositor merely slideshows (~76 % drop rate) because
its single-surface attach pattern has shorter pipeline depth;
chrome's wp_subsurface flow exhausts faster and fully deadlocks.

Validation on ohm (RK3566 PineTab2 / hantro mainline 6.19.10 /
panfrost mesa 26.0.5):

- Pre-patch: chrome v4 stalls at ~6 s under stock KWin 6.6.4.
- Pre-patch + kwin-fourier (watchDmaBuf bypass): stalls at ~22 s.
- Same chrome v4 binary under weston: plays through end-to-end
  (no stall, ~96 % CPU vs KWin's ~50 % when not stalled).

The compositor-side bugs (KWin's watchDmaBuf fence wait, Qt 6
GL_ALPHA on ES 3) have their own patch series (qt6-base-fourier,
kwin-fourier) — but the V4L2 capture pool depth is itself too
shallow for any wayland compositor on this hardware to reliably
keep up. Bumping the floor to 16 gives ~10 buffers of headroom
beyond the H.264 case while still respecting high-DPB codecs
(HEVC, VP9 with deeper reference counts) via the std::max.

Memory cost at 1920x1080 NV12 is +30 MB resident (10 extra buffers
× 3 MB each). On the 4 GB RK3566 reference platform that does not
move the needle.

Fix
---
Floor `v4l2_num_buffers` at 16 when V4L2 is the buffer allocator.
The std::max preserves correctness for codecs requiring more than
14 reference frames.

diff --git a/media/gpu/v4l2/v4l2_video_decoder.cc b/media/gpu/v4l2/v4l2_video_decoder.cc
--- a/media/gpu/v4l2/v4l2_video_decoder.cc
+++ b/media/gpu/v4l2/v4l2_video_decoder.cc
@@ -1199,11 +1199,16 @@
   // If we don't use driver-allocated buffers, request as many as possible
   // (VIDEO_MAX_FRAME) since they are shallow allocations. Otherwise, allocate
   // |num_codec_reference_frames| plus one for the video frame being decoded,
   // and one for our client (presumably an ImageProcessor).
+  // chromium-fourier: floor the V4L2 capture pool at 16 to give us
+  // headroom against KWin/wayland compositor scheduling jitter. Default
+  // (num_codec_reference_frames + 2) yields 6 for H.264 main, equal to
+  // chrome's pipeline depth — first jitter event exhausts the pool and
+  // hard-stalls the decoder. See chromium-fourier KWIN_PIVOT.md.
   const size_t v4l2_num_buffers = use_v4l2_allocated_buffers
-                                      ? num_codec_reference_frames + 2
+                                      ? std::max(num_codec_reference_frames + 2, size_t{16})
                                       : VIDEO_MAX_FRAME;
